Ephemeral Storage in Kubernetes
Overview

Ephemeral storage in Kubernetes is temporary storage used by containers during the lifetime of a Pod.

The data stored in ephemeral storage does not persist.
If the Pod is deleted, restarted, or rescheduled, the data stored in ephemeral storage is lost.

Ephemeral storage is mainly used for:

Temporary files

Logs

Cache data

Intermediate processing data

Where Ephemeral Storage Exists

Ephemeral storage resides on the node's local disk.

It is consumed by the following components:

Container writable layer

emptyDir volumes

Container logs

Image layers

Node Disk
│
├── Container Writable Layer
├── emptyDir Volumes
├── Container Logs
└── Image Layers
Example Pod Using Ephemeral Storage
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: demo-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx

Inside the container, applications may write files to locations such as:

/tmp
/var/log
/app/cache

These files are stored in ephemeral storage.

If the Pod restarts, these files will disappear.

emptyDir Volume (Common Ephemeral Storage)

emptyDir is a Kubernetes volume type that provides temporary storage shared between containers in the same Pod.

The volume is created when the Pod starts and deleted when the Pod is removed.

Example
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: cache-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx
    volumeMounts:
    - mountPath: /cache
      name: cache-volume

  volumes:
  - name: cache-volume
    emptyDir: {}
Lifecycle
Pod Start
   ↓
emptyDir Created
   ↓
Containers use the volume
   ↓
Pod Deleted
   ↓
emptyDir Deleted
Ephemeral Storage Resource Limits

Kubernetes allows defining resource requests and limits for ephemeral storage, similar to CPU and memory.

Example
resources:
  requests:
    ephemeral-storage: "1Gi"
  limits:
    ephemeral-storage: "2Gi"
Meaning
Resource	Description
requests	Minimum storage required
limits	Maximum storage allowed

If a container exceeds the limit:

Pod will be evicted
Node Disk Pressure

If the node disk becomes full, Kubernetes triggers DiskPressure.

When DiskPressure occurs, Kubernetes starts evicting pods to free disk space.

Check Node Status
kubectl describe node <node-name>

Example condition:

Conditions:
DiskPressure = True
Pod Eviction Priority

When storage runs out, Kubernetes evicts pods in the following order:

Pods exceeding ephemeral-storage limits

BestEffort pods

Burstable pods

Guaranteed pods (last to be evicted)

Pods without defined resource limits are more likely to be evicted.

